  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Pulpit Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_sub_title",
        "text": "Verse 8.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " - ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "And at this house, which is high",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " [Heb., ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "And",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "this house shall be high",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "hebrew",
        "text": "עֶלְיון יִהְיֶה",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". Our translators were probably influenced by ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Chronicles 7:21",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", the text of which is ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "hebrew",
        "text": "אֲשֶׁר הָיהָ עֶלְיון",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " which would seem to be an emendation, designed to clear up the difficulty rather than an accidental variation of the text. But here the literal rendering is probably the truer, the meaning being \"this house shall be conspicuous, as an example\" - so the Vulg. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "domus haec erit in exemplum",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". The LXX. accords with the Hebrew text, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greek",
        "text": "ὁ οῖκος οῦτος ἔσται ὁ ὐψηλὸς",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", but the Syriac and Arabic read, \"this house shall be destroyed.\" Keil sees in the words an allusion ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "implicite",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " to ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Deuteronomy 26:19",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", and Deuteronomy 28:1, where God promises to make ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "Israel",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "hebrew",
        "text": "עֶלְיון",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", and says \"the blessing will be turned into a curse.\" The temple should indeed be \"high,\" should be what Israel would have been, but it shall be as a ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "warning",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", etc.; but this connexion is somewhat far fetched and artificial. Thenius would read for, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "hebrew",
        "text": "עִיִּין עֶלְיון",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". \"ruins,\" after ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Micah 3:12",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Jeremiah 26:18",
        "children": []
      },
      {
